This might be a stretch, but "Countries like Albania, Bhutan, and Iceland are less impacted by environmental pollution." It's supported by the passage, but 'pollution' is a fairly broad term that a) might not account for everything and b) relies heavily on the status of neighboring countries for the statement to be true.
Honestly, I'm struggling to find a reasonable inference here.

text_answer.content:
The vocabulary sentences don't really have anything to do with the topic. Usually they're more closely related. 5 is the only one that has to do with education.
The dress code percents seem questionable. According to Google's AI (so grain of salt), 59% of private schools have a school uniform (something the passage specifically mentions in paragraph 4). Dress codes are far less formal and consistent than school uniforms, so at minimum I'd say we need to combine the data. Taking the information given here and what I found online at face value, it'd be more like 80% of public schools have either a school uniform or dress code while 96% of private schools do. While I can't confirm these numbers are correct, it feels more reasonable for private schools to have that higher percent. Year should also be considered with these statistics when possible. The 2013-2014 school year seemed to have the highest percentage of schools that had a strict dress code, but it's been declining to decades lows since (I could only find to 2020).

I think one of the issues I'm running into in this passage is that there are a LOT of statistics, but no examples of what those statistics specifically mean. It's fine to say "31% of students believe dress codes are unfairly enforced based on gender," and I do respect that the statistic and the reasons behind the statistic are probably true. However, without an example of what the 31% are referring to, it's just a number. Keep in mind that if 31% think this way, 69% don't. It's a percent which could just as easily refer to students who genuinely don't think gender discrimination is happening or it could refer to students who haven't thought about it, so stating what the 31% is talking about is crucial for clarity.
Other questions include: what clothing styles have been unfairly targeted, how have students felt body shamed by dress codes (and how are they even linked), and why are students of color most affected? Again, I do respect that these statements are probably true, but a student who has never had to deal with dress code violations may not have thought about their impact before and won't understand the issues presented.

The hyper focus on statistics means all three Key Details questions are focused on percents.
Key Details question 3 is worded wrong. It's presenting a compare/contrast that requires two statistics (percent of high-poverty vs low-poverty), but it only gives the high-poverty percentage in the answer.
The Analyzing Information question overlaps with Key Details question 2 and the main idea.

For the inference, "schools face the challenge of balancing safety and structure with personal autonomy."
I'm not going give an alternative because I think this passage needs a significant overhaul.

Key Details 3 is fairly obvious since the passage only mentions one of those concepts.
The Analyzing Information question gives itself away.

I'm going to skip offering an alternative since I think this passage needs a substantial rewrite.

The statistics should have dates.

A discussion of laptop vs smartphone gaming should also look at the available titles for each system, specifically their relative quality to one another and the way the games interact with their respective hardware. Laptops generally have access to all the major gaming titles released for PCs but are severely limited by their processing capabilities when placed next to most desktops. This means the 91% vs 80% statistic is only a part of the relevant data, since I'm guessing the less affulent laptop users are likely to also have older. less capable hardware, further reducing their ability to play certain games. On the other hand, there aren't usually any restrictions on the apps smart phones can access. However, the games developed for smart phones are traditionally of lower quality in graphics, gameplay, and storytelling due to both the inherent hardware limitations and a difference in business model philosophies.
To give the necessary space for this part of the discussion, I'd certainly avoid looking at the economic disparities, since that's not really relevant to the discussion. I'd also only limit the focus on the different hardware capabilities to one or two paragraphs rather than the four here.

Soft no on appropriateness. While I appreciate the mention of sexual orientation as a social category, I'm hesitant to include it in the text. America is currently still divided on this issue and our material needs to be accessible to those parts of the country that are... less accepting of this idea. On a legal side, we do have centers in states like Florida where even being able to include mentions of same-sex relationships is somewhat up in the air currently. Ultimately it's not really the point of the passage and probably should be removed. Flagging so a decision can be made.
Soft yes on bias. I wasn't going to include this originally, but the focus on neurdivergent people means there's no consideration for the needs and requirements of certain professional environments or neurotypical people. That would normally be fine, since the point of the passage is to discuss neudiversity, but Key Details 2's focus on modifying environments highlights that there's no consideration for why the environment was designed a specific way to begin with. In some situations, accommodating neurodivergency goes counter to the scenario and creates more problems than it fixes. Not really sure what, if anything, I'd do to address this issue. Maybe changing Key Details 2 to a different question is enough to avoid having to go through those weeds? Another might be a look into why neurodivergent people struggle in neurotypical environments. Either way, flagging so a decision can be made.
Soft yes on false/unverifiable information, mostly because the inclusion of the 2023 study feels non-sequitur. The preceding sentence indicates that neurodivergent people excel in areas but doesn't suggest anything about well-being or quality of life. So the for instance that starts the last sentence of the paragraph feels like it's setting up an example of, maybe, how these people recognize patterns before going into something completely unrelated. This affects Key Details 1.
Key Details 3's answers should include more overlap. Like, A should be ADHD, synesthesia, and bipolar disorder. Bipolar is, technically, a neurodivergence, but it's not mentioned in the passage. However, saying 'Memory loss, confusion, and fatigue' is obviously wrong since none of those relate to neurodiversity and aren't mentioned.

A is valid. The answer key switches the 'many' mentioned in the answer choice to 'all' as a way to explain why it's wrong. That said, I'm not sure we want to include that answer, so...

Vocabulary sentence 1 is a no. At the very least it shouldn't be the first vocabulary sentence, but I also think there's a better sentence out there that doesn't have slavery so upfront.
Vocabulary sentences 2 and 5 are interchangeable.
An idea what $300 dollars means in 'today's' money would help students understand why it was unaffordable for some. Most of the inflation calculators online only go back to 1913, but there was one that extrapolated and suggests it'd be about $7,500 today (though if the AI can get a more reliable number, that'd be amazing).
Nit pick: mentioning Republican anything without further context is iffy. This was when the Republican party was the progressive party and Democrats were the conservative party, before FDR switched them. Yes, it was the Republican party who started the draft, but they were also the party who were championing the war with the South.
The way "civil War freedmen's associations" is capitalized feels wrong, though I don't know how it's supposed to look.
I will note that I'm super mixed on this passage. It touches on so many problematic issues (racism, slavery, the civil war, unchecked violence), but it keeps those topics reasonably surface level by focusing on the facts without exploring the worst aspects of the event. It also doesn't invite further questions from the students (which made coming up with replacement essay prompts particularly difficult).
The Key Idea is more a combination of answers A and E: "The first federal draft law brought social, racial, and economic tensions to a boil which lead to rioting in New York City."

For the inference question, "The Conscription Act allowed wealthy citizens to avoid military service by paying $300 for a substitute, creating deep resentment among working-class residents who could not afford this fee. This class disparity ... created a volatile atmosphere that would soon erupt into chaos."
C is close but needs to be slightly adjusted for accuracy. "The Tribune newspaper likely supported policies that favored wealthy citizens over working-class ones."

Warp and weft are jargon in this context. They're not even explained in the passage.
The timeline is really hard to establish in this passage. It just jumps around so, so much We go from Homo erectus and Homo antecessor (800,000 years ago), to Egyptian linen (7000 years ago) and Chinese silk (6000 years ago), then back to 170,000 years ago with the emergence of human body lice. After that there's a discussion of the development of textiles that gives no reference to dates before jumping to the 1930s. It's just really hard to track what's happening when and how one development leads into the next.
This passage is strangely devoid of any discussion related to clothing as fashion. Not really a huge issue, and I didn't notice it in my first read, but it's a weird thing to overlook when discussing clothing.

The phrase "recent COVID-19 pandemic" gives this passage a shelf life. It should be fine if the word recent is dropped, though.

This passage is a little all over the place and doesn't really follow its basic premise. We do get a couple of historical events, but the Spanish Flu is the only place the essay comes close to explaining the global impact, which is limited to it affecting one-third of the world's population.
Structurally it should probably start with a broad examination of how diseases spread before going into the largest global pandemics and their respective legacies. These would include the Bubonic plaque (which has had 6 recorded pandemics, including the second most deadly pandemic, and one as recent as 1960), the Spanish flu and other influenza pandemics, and COVID-19. HIV/AIDs is also a potential option as it has the third largest death toll and longest running pandemic, but the politics surrounding that one is problematic so best to avoid (for this essay certainly and probably in general).
A combination of the last two paragraphs would work as the conclusion. I'd probably remove the new challenges, since there's no explanation of how factory farming, genetic modification, or antimicrobial resistance create new challenges and aren't directly related to historical pandemics.

Given the above, the Key Idea isn't really B since we don't know how historical disease outbreaks have shaped human society.

text_answer.content:
For the vocabulary, methodical and systemic can go in sentences 3, 4, or 6 and stratigraphic can go in sentences 4 or 6.

Starting with the bias, I'm a little mixed on the mentions of colonialism as a primary motivator for early archaeology. It's a valid perspective regarding what was happening at the time, it's largely supported, and we as a global society are still working through the consequences. However, I'm not sure that period of time (the 17th and 18th centuries) can be considered true archaeology. Britannica (https://www.britannica.com/science/archaeology) describes the era more akin to art collecting than true archaeology.
Archaeology as a discipline had its earliest approximation in 1802 and the 'official' start in the 1870s with Heinrich Schliemann. And while the passage does mention Heinrich, there's nothing specific about hows, whys, and whens. Furthermore, any discussion of actual archaeology techniques is relegated to the concluding paragraph despite the field of study supposedly being the main focus of the passage.
Structurally I'd combine paragraphs 2 and 3 while only broadly mentioning the motivations of early treasure hunters before getting into the weeds of archaeology and its early development.
I also question the conclusion that archaeology simply began as a result of European museums becoming overwhelmed with "looted" artifacts. That's somewhat inconsistent with the five pillars and ignores the broader scientific developments of the time. The Britannica article specifically points to developments in geology, the development of a prehistoric time-line (stone, bronze, and iron ages), and the development of Darwin's theory of evolution. Each of these motivators both enhance the capabilities of archaeology but also speak directly to the scientific purpose of the discipline (as opposed to 'we're overwhelmed').
On a related note: I've recently run into a number of passages that seem to gloss over factual details and give broad overviews of topics. This does not work for 11th grade.

Key Details 3 is too broad.

For the inference, B is not supported. Although the Age of Enlightenment is mentioned, there's no exploration of the specific societal changes of the time. Further, the passage suggests archaeology was limited at this time as financing was hard to come by.
A and C are reasonable.

Too broad for 11th grade and it's a little jumpy in its structure. The broad nature also gives it an overall pro-AI feel by minimizing the potential impact on jobs and the workforce. Many of these AI passages include sections that suggest empathy and creativity are going to be highly prized when programs like this one, where AI is being used for a creative purpose, exist. A large part of the recent WGA and SAG-AFTRA strikes were related to AI tools as well, and they're both solidly in the creative space. I haven't marked it as factually incorrect because the basic idea is still valid, but in this case the passage includes critical thinking and problem-solving on this list, which are what AI is especially adapt at.
All the Key Details questions are statistics.

In addition to C, I would argue that D is valid for the inference question as "The ability to effectively manage teams, lead innovation initiatives, and build relationships" are skills that not everyone has. People who have strengths that align with AI capabilities aren't going to suddenly learn how to be skilled in social situations, especially given that there are literal development disorders like autism that make social skills especially difficult.
